Molecularly characterized mutants are blocked in the biosynthesis of abscisic acid (ABA), or in ABA signaling.
Viviparous mutants often have other phenotypes, notably colorless aleurone from suppression of anthocyanins (vp1) and white endosperm , from blocks in carotenoid synthesis (lw2, vp5, ps1/vp7).
Viviparous mutants in maize may be kernel lethal , or if rescued prior to ear desiccation, either viable, or seedling lethal.

Viable mutants are known for vp1, which encodes a transcription factor involved in ABA signaling, and vp14, which encodes an NCED enzyme that cleaves carotenoids to provide xanthoxin, an ABA precursor.
Seedling lethal mutants include vp5, ps1/vp7 and vp9 , which block production of carotenoid precursors for ABA synthesis .
Vp10 and vp15, both deficient in synthesis of the molybdenum cofactor(MoCo) required for ABA synthesis and other pathways.
